<h3><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Blin_language&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6" title="Edit section: Latin alphabet">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline" id="Latin_alphabet">Latin alphabet</span></h3>
<p>In 1985 the <a href="/wiki/Eritrean_People%27s_Liberation_Front" title="Eritrean People's Liberation Front">Eritrean People's Liberation Front</a> decided to use the <a href="/wiki/Latin_alphabet" title="Latin alphabet">Latin alphabet</a> for Blin and all<sup class="Template-Fact" title="This claim needs references to reliable sources from February 2009" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed">citation needed</a></i>]</sup> other minority <a href="/wiki/Languages_of_Eritrea" title="Languages of Eritrea">languages in Eritrea</a>. This was largely a political decision: the Ge'ez script is associated with <a href="/wiki/Christianity" title="Christianity">Christianity</a> because of its <a href="/wiki/Ge%27ez_language" title="Ge'ez language">liturgical use</a>. The Latin alphabet is seen as being more neutral. In 1993 the government set up a committee to standardize the Blin language and the Latin-based orthography.</p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Blin_language&amp;action=edit&amp;section=7" title="Edit section: See also">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline" id="See_also">See also</span></h2>
<ul>
<li><a href="/wiki/Bilen" title="Bilen">Blin people</a></li>
</ul>
